"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The x-coordinate in the plt.text() function should be a scalar value, but a datetime object is provided. Matplotlib's text function uses data coordinates by default, so the x-coordinate should be a value that corresponds to the x-axis values, which in this case are datetime objects. However, the y-coordinate seems to be a relative value between 0 and 1, which might not match the y-axis values. It would be better to use the ax.text() function and specify the transform parameter to 'ax.transAxes' to use relative coordinates.\",\n  \"patch\": \"17c17\\n< plt.text(datetime.datetime.strptime(\\\"2013-01-05\\\"), 0.5, \\\"SAMPLE\\\")\\n---\\n> ax.text(0.5, 0.9, \\\"SAMPLE\\\", transform=ax.transAxes)\\n\"\n}"